@endnode

@node intro "Introduction.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Intro
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   This is a simple but quite useful backup tool. It simply copies
   files and links from one directory to another. Of cource it only
   copies files that are different in some way, like size or date etc.
   It does not scan the file contents for differencies. A separate
   verify byte-by-byte function is available for that.

   It also has a skiplist where you can add directories and/or big
   files (512kB+) that you don't want to be backed up. Useful to prevent
   backing up temp files or cache directories.

   It also has another feature; cleaning, that makes it possible to
   remove old files from the backup unit (Target) by comparing all
   files on the backup with the files on the work unit (Source) and
   delete the files that no longer exist on the work unit from the
   backup.

   BackUp has a GUI which is used by default, but it can also be
   executed completely automated from shell scripts.

   BackUp does not use any lowlevel access to the disks, only
   standard OS-functions are used so if your current configuration
   of your computer can handle big partitions and files >4GB, so
   can BackUp. I have backed up 34GB of data without problems.
   Since BackUp is written for OS2/68k it may report wrong statistics
   for single files over 2GB but the backup itself is good.


@endnode

@node req "Requirements.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Requirements
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   OS version 37+
   Asl.library v37+
   GadTools.library v37+
   512kB of memory for the copy buffer. 1MB when verifying.

   Can be run even before/without startup-sequence to make emergency
   backup or restore in case of emergency. Does not depend on any
   external, 3rd-party libraries.


@endnode

@node disc "Disclaimer.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Disclaimer
  ~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   I WILL NOT BE HELD RESPONSIBLE FOR ANY DAMAGE OR LOSS OF DATA THAT
   THIS PROGRAM MIGHT CAUSE YOUR SYSTEM OR DATA!

   I have put a lot of energy to make that actual backup and cleaning
   procedures completely error-free. I believe that is very important
   for a backup tool. The GUI, the inter-process communication, and
   the statistics calculations might have some bugs though, but this
   should not affect the actual operation.


@endnode

@node usage "Usage.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}Usage
  ~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

  Start the program, it has a GUI in GadTools.

  Or start it from CLI with @{"arguments" link cli}.

  There is a lister with some information in. This will be updated
  during the backup and some statistics will be shown at the end
  of the backup process.

  @{b}Source@{ub}
    This is where to copy from. Enter a directory here or pick one
    using the "Asl"-button. Everything in this directory including
    all subdirectories will be copied except entries found in the
    skiplist.

    CLI: SOURCE/K
    Default is what was previously saved from the GUI.

  @{b}Target@{ub}
    This is where to copy everything from the Source to.

    CLI: TARGET/K
    Default is what was previously saved from the GUI.

  @{b}Skiplist...@{ub}
    This will open a window with a list in which you can add directories,
    and files that are larger than 512kB, that you don't want to be included
    in your backup, or be removed when cleaning the Target.

    There is a switch to allow directories in the skiplist to be created even
    though their contents will not be copied. Useful when backing up programs
    that have a logs/ or cache/ directory for example, where the directories
    themselves are important, but not their contents.

    Note: If the cleaner finds delete protected files and you say you want
    to leave those files, they will temporarely be added to the skiplist.
    You can observe this if you press Pause when cleaning and enter the skiplist.
    Do not worry, they will be removed when the cleaning is finished.
    Therefore you should not be confused if you find unknown directories in
    the skiplist during a cleaning process.

    The unit names for the dirs/files in this skiplist must be the same as the
    one in the Source (or the Target when cleaning)!
    Ex. If you have a path "Work:Stuff/" in the skiplist, you cannot write
    "DH1:" in the Source (or Target), you must write "Work:" else the files
    and directoies will not be recognized by the filter. Also using assigns
    in the skiplist will not work because of the same reason unless you also
    use the same assign in the Source (or Target) of course.

    CLI: SKIPFILE/K
    Default is what was previously saved from the GUI.

      @{b}Add file@{ub}   - Get a file requester where you can pick files larger
                   than 512kB to add to the list.
                   The requester will keep opening until you click Cancel
                   to make it easy to add several files.

                   The reason not to be able to filter smaller files is
                   because the backup process would be very slow if every
                   tiny file needed to be checked against the skiplist.

      @{b}Add dir@{ub}    - Get a file requester where you can pick a directory to
                   add to the list. The requester will keep opening until
                   you click Cancel to make it easy to add several files.

      @{b}Remove@{ub}     - Remove the selected entry from the list.

      @{b}Clear list@{ub} - Clear the whole list.

      @{b}Load a list@{ub}
        This opens an Asl-requester for you to choose a textfile to load
        as skiplist.

        CLI: SKIPFILE/K

      @{b}Save the list@{ub}
        This opens an Asl-requester for you to choose a place to save
        the skiplist.

      @{b}Close@{ub}      - Close the skiplist window.


        @{fg shine}@{u}The menu for the skiplist window@{uu}@{fg text}

      @{b}Load skiplist...@{ub}
        This opens an Asl-requester for you to choose a textfile to load
        as skiplist.

        CLI: SKIPFILE/K

      @{b}Save skiplist...@{ub}
        This opens an Asl-requester for you to choose a place to save
        he skiplist.

      @{b}Set paths to match the Source for backup@{ub}
        This will change the paths in the skiplist to match the Source
        path so that they can be used when backing up. Typically needed
        after cleaning. BackUp will also detect this and do it automatically.

      @{b}Set paths to match the Target for cleaning@{ub}
        This will change the paths in the skiplist to match the Target
        path so that they can be used when cleaning.
        BackUp will detect this and do it automatically.

      @{b}About@{ub}
        This will just show the about-requester.

      @{b}Close@{ub}
        This will close the skiplist window.


  @{b}Clean@{ub}
    This will scan the Target and remove all files and directories from
    the Target that does not exists in the Source anymore. This is useful
    as you probably often rename or remove files from the source as you
    are working, and when you then backup, all the renamed and deleted
    files will still be present in the Target (if you have made earlier
    backups) and in time the Target will grow a lot larger than the Source.

    Use Clean to remove all old files from the Target, then make a new backup.
    If you click Clean first, before Backup, you will be asked if a backup
    should be run automatically when the cleaning has finished.

    Files and directories that have been added to the skiplist will not be
    removed from the Target by the cleaner. Be sure to set the paths in the
    skiplist to correspond to the Target instead of the Source when cleaning.
    You will be asked about this, but can also be done manually from the menu
    within the Skiplist window.

    CLI: CLEAN/S
    Default is to not start cleaning automatically.

  @{b}BackUp@{ub}
    This will start the actual backup by copying all files and directories
    from the Source to the Target.

    See the skiplist if there are files and directories you do not want to backup.

    CLI: BACKUP/S
    Default is to not start backing up automatically.

  @{b}Stop@{ub}
    This will stop the backup or cleaning process.

  @{b}Pause@{ub}
    This will pause the backup, cleaning or verify process until you press
    Backup or Clean again, or select verify byte-by-byte again from the menu.
    Then it will continue were it was.

    Note: When pausing in the middle of a large file, this file can
    be changed or deleted in both the Source and the Target, but when you
    continue the backup this file will be skipped and deleted from the
    target if it has been altered during pause.

    Also note that pausing a backup or verify while processing a huge file
    (over 4GB), it may not be able to continue correctly, depending on the
    file system 32bit<->64bit interface implementation. Untested.

  @{b}Quit@{ub}
    This will exit the program.

    CLI: AUTOQUIT/S
    Default is false.

    @{fg shine}@{u}The menu for the main window@{uu}@{fg text}

  @{i}Project@{ui}

    @{b}Pick Source...@{ub}
      Pick a source path using an Asl-requester.

    @{b}Pick Target...@{ub}
      Pick a Target path using an Asl-requester.


    @{b}Save preferences@{ub}
      This will save the Source- and Target paths, and all other paths and
      the main window position.


    @{b}Help@{ub}
      This will display the message shown when the program is started.

    @{b}About...@{ub}
      Show some info about the program.

    @{b}OnyxSoft...@{ub}
      Show some info about OnyxSoft.

    @{b}Quit@{ub}
      This will exit the program.

      CLI: AUTOQUIT/S



  @{i}Backup@{ui}

    @{b}Backup by the archive-bit@{ub}
      Use this switch if you would like BackUp to only copy files
      that do not have the archive bit set in the source, and
      then set the archive bit on source files and directories that
      were successfully copied.

      This is how many backup tools work. I chose a slightly different
      approach as the default method (not using this switch) in BackUp
      because I didn't want BackUp to alter the source files in any way.

      CLI: USEARCHIVE/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Copy archived files that don't exist on target@{ub}
      This switch is useful if any files have been removed from the
      target, or if this is the first backup attempt. It will ensure
      that all files are copied if they do not exist in the target from
      a previous backup, even if they already have the archive bit set.

      Without this switch BackUp only looks at the archive bit on the
      source files and ignores every file on the source that has the
      archive bit already set.

      With this switch the logic is this:
        If a file or dir does not exist on the target -> Copy the file/dir.
        If a file or dir does not have the archive bit set -> Copy the file/dir.
        Set the archive bit on the source file or directory.

      Without this switch the logic is this:
        If a file or dir does not have the archive bit set -> Copy the file/dir.
        Set the archive bit on the source file or directory.
        Completely ignore al files that already have the archive bit set.


    @{b}Never copy Amiga protection bits@{ub}
      Prevents BackUp from setting the protection bits after backing up
      files. Sometimes useful when backing up over Samba or USB or some
      other way to any non-Amiga file system.

      CLI: NOPROTBITS/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Never copy Amiga file comments@{ub}
      Prevents BackUp from setting the file comment after backing up
      files. Sometimes useful when backing up over Samba or USB or some
      other way to any non-Amiga file system.

      CLI: NOFILECOMMENTS/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Only copy newer files@{ub}
      Sometimes it may be desirable to only copy files from the Source
      that are newer than the files in the Target.

      CLI: COPYONLYNEWER/S

    @{b}Copy softlinks as files and directories@{ub}
      Since v1.50 BackUp will follow and copy all softlinks and tries
      to recreate them as good as possible on the backup.
      With this switch you can make BackUp instead follow the softlinks
      and copy the actual files and directories the links point to instead
      of copying the softlink itself.

      Very useful if you like to make a copy of a directory or partition
      without links in it to be able to burn it on a CD.

      Note: A warning must be issued because following directory links
      can be dangerous if there are any link loops! BackUp will handle
      link loops by not recursing indefinately, but the backup will
      not be an equal copy of the source. Use Verify byte-by-byte to
      find out.

      Note 2: Since the actual file will be copied several times when
      using this switch (since both the original file and any links
      pointing to it will be copied as files), the backup may become
      significantly larger than the source!

      CLI: FOLLOWLINKS/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Ignore all links@{ub}
      Since v1.50 BackUp will copy softlinks also. This switch makes
      BackUp ignore all links as if they didn't exist. Before v1.50
      BackUp didn't understand links and generated error messages
      when they were encountered.

      @{u}Note well again:@{uu} The only protection against link loops is
      that BackUp has a maximum depth of 100 directories. If a link
      loop is encountered, BackUp will be stuck in this loop until
      it reaches the maximum depth before it retracts and continues.
      (A link loop is a directory link connected further up in the tree.
       Ex: "Work:prog/data/dirlink/" is a link directory that points to
       f.ex. "Work:prog/". The resulting backed up tree will be this:
       "Work:prog/data/dirlink/data/dirlink/data/dirlink/data/dirlink/[...]x100")

      CLI: IGNORELINKS/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Ignore all read errors@{ub}
      This switch will disable the checking of all read errors that may
      occur during the backup. This can be very useful when trying to
      use BackUp to salvage files from a crashed harddisk or something.
      In this case BackUp will force reading of the complete files
      ignoring all read errors and just write whatever it could get
      instead of just stop with an error message.

    @{b}Create skipped directories@{ub}
      Directories that have been added to the skiplist will normally
      not be created (since v1.44). But if it is desired to have these
      directories created too, but remain empty, this switch can be used.

      A practical example would be when a program is backed up that has
      two driectories in which it stores logs and a disk cache. The
      logs and the cache will be obsolete when the backup is eventually
      needed, but the directories must still exist or the program may
      not work properly.

      CLI: CREATESKIPDIRS/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Target is FAT file system@{ub}
      Select this when making backing up to a disk/partition with a FAT
      file system on it. This will make BackUp understand that it does
      not need to copy all files with only one second difference in the
      file timestamp. It is effective when making an incremental/second
      backup when there are many old unchanged files already on the backup
      disk.

      If this flag is off, BackUp will auto-detect if the partition is
      FAT and ask you after 20 files or so. In shell mode it will not ask
      but just enable the flag silently.

      There is little harm in having this enabled all the time. There is
      no magic, only slightly looser detection of the change of a file's
      timestamp.

      CLI: TARGETISFAT/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Do not copy files larger than N bytes@{ub}
      When this flag is selected only files that have a file size equal
      or smaller than the "file size limit for large files" (see below)
      will be copied.

      Useful to backup for example your e-mail archive but not huge e-mails,
      or digicam pictures if you have mixed original pictures with scaled
      down version and only want to backup the scaled down versions.

      CLI: (see below)

    @{b}Set file size limit for skipping large files...@{ub}
      Opens a window where you can set a maximum size of files that should
      be copied. Only files with a size larger than this number will be
      copied if the flag @{b}Do not copy files larger than N bytes@{ub} is also
      selected in the menu.

      NOTE: This program is pure 32-bit and will not recognize the correct
      size for files 4GB and larger. You need to put any such files into
      the skiplist manually if you do not want them to be copied.

      CLI: SIZELIMIT/N
      Default is what was previously saved from the GUI. To disable this
      feature (if it was saved as enabled), supply a negative value.

    @{b}Test mode!@{ub}
      This enabled/disables the test mode. Enabling test mode means
      that a backup or cleaning will not take place. It will just
      be simulated if you press Backup or Clean. This is useful if
      you are uncertain about how much space that will be required, or
      if you just want a log over what BackUp would do in case of a
      real backup or cleaning.

      Ignored when verifying.

      CLI: TESTMODE/S
      Default is false.



  @{i}Misc@{ui}

    @{b}Load a skiplist...@{ub}
      Use an Asl-requester to pick a (new) skiplist file.

    @{b}Edit the Skiplist...@{ub}
      This will just open the skiplist window.

    @{b}Save stats as...@{ub}
      This will save whatever is in the listview in the main window
      to a textfile that you choose with and Asl-requester.

      CLI: STATFILE/K
      Default is what was previously saved from the GUI.

    @{b}Save errors as...@{ub}
      This will open an asl-requester so that you can pick a file
      to save the error list.

      CLI: ERRFILE/K
      Default is what was previously saved from the GUI.

    @{b}Don't clear stat window@{ub}
      Normally BackUp clears the stats in the window when you
      start an operation and again after an operation is finished.
      With this option you can prevent this so that you can get
      a history over what you have done.

      CLI: DONTCLRSTAT/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Clear stats window now@{ub}
      This will simply clear the main window's listview.

    @{b}Verify byte-by-byte after backup@{ub}
      Automatically read and compare all files after a backup has been run.

      See the next section for more info.

      CLI note: When starting BackUp from CLI with BACKUP/S or VERIFY/S,
      this switch will be ignored. If you want verify after backup when
      starting from CLI you need to specify BACKUP VERIFY on the commandline.

    @{b}Verify byte-by-byte@{ub}
      Run a byte-by-byte verification of the source againste the target
      to check for any differences in any file. Verify will detect all
      differences, such as different date, comments, protection bits,
      size and also file contents (if the file size is equal).

      This is a rather slow process and does not normally have to be run,
      but it can be useful if you suspect there are errors in the backup.
      Non-detectable errors can be caused by transmission bit-errors over
      the IDE cable if it is set to operate too fast. UDMA133 can sometimes
      cause transmission errors with wierd crashes and misbehavior as a
      consequence.

      If you suspect errors, use this function. Make a backup and then run
      Verify to test. If there are differences in file contents (see the log),
      then run verify again to see if the difference is now in another file.
      If that is the case you have IDE transfer errors or you have bad RAM.
      Try lowering the IDE transfer speed, backup and verify again. Repeat
      until there are no errors.

      Note: If you have enabled "Copy links as files and directories", then
      verify will tell you there is a difference in file type between your
      links in the source and the files in the target. That is ok.

      CLI: VERIFY/S



  @{i}Log @{ui}

    Logging can be done to up to three different places simultanously.
    This log is what directories BackUp traverse and what files it
    encouters and copies or deletes. Statistics are written to the end
    of the log file with a blank line as a separator.

    A line in the log will contain a character followed by a space
    followed by a file or directory name. See @{"log file codes" link logcodes}.


    @{b}Log to stat window@{ub}
      If this is enabled logging will be made to the main window's
      stats list.

      CLI: LOGSTAT/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Log to file@{ub}
      This will log to a file. Specify what file with @{b}Pick log file...@{ub}
      or with the CLI argument.

      CLI: LOGFILE/K
      Default is false.

    @{b}Log to console@{ub}
      This will log to the shell that BackUp was started from.

      CLI: LOGCON/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Verbose logging@{ub}
      Log every file that is copied or deleted too, not just
      directories and large (512kB+) files.

      CLI: VERBOSELOG/S
      Default is false.

    @{b}Pick log file...@{ub}
      Use this to select a file to use as logfile.

      CLI: LOGFILE/K
      Default is what was previously saved from the GUI,
      but no logging will be done.

    @{b}Open the error list...@{ub}
      This will open the window which will display all errors that might
      have been encountered during an operation. The windows opens
      automatically if there were any errors.

        @{b}Sort@{ub}  - This will sort the error list.

        @{b}Save log...@{ub}  - This will open an asl-requester so that you can pick
                a file to save the error list in.

        @{b}Clear@{ub} - This will clear the error list.

        @{b}Help@{ub} - Show a list with descriptions of the error codes.

        @{b}Close@{ub} - Close the error list window.


          @{fg shine}@{u}The menu for the error list window@{uu}@{fg text}

        @{b}Save error list@{ub}
          The same as the Save button.

        @{b}Error codes@{ub}
          This will open a requester explaining all error
          codes for the files in the error list. You can
          also print this error code list to a console from
          within this requester if you want to save it.

          See @{"error codes" link errorcodes}.

        @{b}About@{ub}
          This will just show the about-requester.

        @{b}Close@{ub}
          This will close the error list window.



@endnode

@node errorcodes "Error codes"

  @{fg shine}@{b}List of error codes in the error window
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

     Arch:      Could not set the archive bit on a source file or dir.

     OpenR:     Could not open a file for reading during backup or verify.

     OpenW:     Could not open a file for writing during backup.

     OpenV:     Could not open a target file for reading during verify.

     Read:      Read error during file copying.

     Write:     Write error during file copying.


     LockDir:   Could not lock a directory.

     ExDir:     Could not examine a directory.

     CreateDir: Could not create a directory.

     SkipDir:   Could not create a directory that was in the skiplist.


     DelDir:    Could not delete a directory.

     DelFile:   Could not delete a file.

     DelLink:   Could not delete a link.

     Unprot:    Could not unprotect a dir or file.

     Skipped:   Skipped deleting a dir or file due to protection.


     MetaC:     Could not update file comment on a target file or directory.

     MetaD:     Could not update the file date on a target file or directory.

     MetaP:     Could not update protection bits on a target file or directory.


     LockLink:  Unable to lock a softlink target and "Copy links as
                files" have been selected.

     MakeLink:  Unable to create a softlink.

     ReadLink:  Unable to read a softlink.

     SoftLink:  A softlink points to another softlink and "Copy links
                as files" have been selected.

     Dir?File:  Could not determine if it was a file or directory.
                It is probably a link of some sort.


@endnode

@node logcodes "Logfile code explanation"

  @{fg shine}@{b}Codes in the logfile
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

  Here is an explanation of the different character codes in the logfile:

     @{u}Generic codes:@{uu}
     » - A directory was entered (verbose only)
     S - A file or directory was skipped because it was in the skiplist.
     s - A file was skipped because it was larger than the file size limit.
     F - A large file encountered (over 512kB).
     R - A file reads beyond end-of-file. Probably over 4GB.
     d - A file was deleted if the backup was interrupted while
         copying a large file.
     l - A link was ignored.
     . - The SFS/2,JXFS ".recycled" dir was skipped.
     E - There was an error reading or creating a directory.
     e - There was an error backing up or cleaning a file.

     @{u}Backup specific codes:@{uu}
     f - A small file copied during backup.
     F - A large file copied.
     C - A directory created during backup.
     L - A link was created during backup.
     d - A target file deleted after stop or error.
     A - Set the archive bit on a backup'ed directory in the source.
         (verbose only)
     a - Set the archive bit on a backup'ed file in the source.
         (verbose only)
     M - Metadata (protection bits, file comment, filedate) was set
         on a file or deirectory. (verbose only)
     m - Failed setting metadata (protection bits, file comment,
         filedate) on a file or directory. (verbose only)

     @{u}Cleaning specific codes:@{uu}
     D - A directory deleted.
     d - A file deleted.
     L - A link was deleted.

     @{u}Verifying specific codes:@{uu}
     Z - File size was different.
     M - Metadata was different.
     C - File contents is different.
     f - A file does not exist on the target.
     d - A directory does not exist on the target.
     t - Not the same type. For example source is a file but target
         is a directory or link.


@endnode

@node cli "CLI usage.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}How to use BackUp from CLI
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

  BackUp has a number of CLI-arguments that you can specify if
  you start BackUp from a shell.

  Note that if you start BackUp from a shell without any arguments
  it will behave exactly as if it was started from Workbench and
  load all settings. Only when at least one arguments is supplied
  it will not load the settings for the switches (/S arguments)
  but leave all switches off so you can decide with CLI arguments
  which switches you would like to use.

  SOURCE/K
    Used to specify the source that shall be backed up.
    If omitted the default path saved in the GUI will be used.

  TARGET/K
    Used to specify the target to copy the source to.
    If omitted the default path saved in the GUI will be used.

  BACKUP/S
    If you specify this then the backup process will start
    immediately when BackUp is started. The GUI will still be
    opened.

  CLEAN/S
    If you specify this then the cleaning process will start
    immediately when BackUp is started. The GUI will still be
    opened. If you specify both CLEAN and BACKUP the cleaning
    will be performed first, then the backup.

  VERIFY/S
    Runs a byte-by-byte verification of the file contents  between
    the source and the target. If CLEAN and/or BACKUP is specified
    as well, VERIFY will run last.

  AUTOQUIT/S
    If you specify this together with BACKUP and/or CLEAN or VERIFY,
    BackUp will quit immediately when the process has completed and
    eventual logs have been saved. If you don't specify neither
    BACKUP nor CLEAN nor VERIFY then AUTOQUIT will be ignored.

    This is useful if you want to use BackUp in a script and
    run BackUp several times automatically after each other for
    backing up many different locations.

  SHELLMODE/S
    If you specify this together with BACKUP and/or CLEAN, BackUp
    will not open its GUI until it has finished. Adding AUTOQUIT
    will prevent the GUI from ever opening. Therefore, the
    combination of SHELLMODE and AUTOQUIT is useful for backing
    up in the background.

    When in shell mode, the process can be interrupted by pressing
    Ctrl-C. The GUI can be opened by pressing Ctrl-D.

    Do not forget to add FORCEDELETE or SKIPDELETE when cleaning
    to be sure there will not be any interaction during the clean
    process. However, if you are uncertain if you have any delete
    protected files it may be wise to let the requester open by
    not specifying any of these two switches.

  USEARCHIVE/S
    Use this switch if you would like BackUp to only copy files
    which does not have the archive bit set in the source, and
    then set the archive bit on source files that were successfully
    copied. This is how many backup tools work.
    
    I chose a slightly different approach as the default method
    (i.e. when not using this switch) in BackUp because I didn't
    want BackUp to alter the source files in any way.

  COPYONLYNEWER/S
    This will only copy newer files from the source to the target,
    based on the file date.

  TARGETISFAT/S
    Enables the FAT file system timestamp recognition.

    Use this when making backing up to a disk/partition with a FAT
    file system on it. This will make BackUp understand that it does
    not need to copy all files with only one second difference in the
    file timestamp. It is effective when making an incremental/second
    backup when there are many old unchanged files already on the backup
    disk.

    If this parameter is not used, BackUp will auto-detect if the
    partition is FAT and ask you after 20 files or so. In shell mode it
    will not ask but just enable the flag silently.

    NOTE: File comments will not be set when using this mode.

  TESTMODE/S
    Specify that backup or clean should be run in test mode without
    affecting any data on disk.

  FOLLOWLINKS/S
    Instead of recreate softlinks on the target, BackUp will follow
    softlinks and copy them as files. This means that BackUp
    will not create links, it will instead copy the file or
    directory each link points to to the target.

  IGNORELINKS/S
    This switch will make BackUp ignore links. Default is to
    recreate the link on the target

  NOPROTBITS/S
    Do not copy and set any Amiga protection bits when backing up.

  NOFILECOMMENTS/S
    Do not copy and set any Amiga file comments when backing up.

  CREATESKIPDIRS/S
    Create empty directories for those directories that are in the
    skiplist instead of ignoring them completely.

  SIZELIMIT/N
    This is used both as a switch to enable the file size limitation
    feature and to specify the file size limit. Using a file size
    limit will prevent backup of files that are larger than this size.

    By default this feature will be used if it has been saved in the
    preference. To disable this feature from shell you can specify a
    negative size, such as SIZELIMIT = -1.

  FORCEDELETE/S
    During the cleaning process BackUp normally asks you if you like
    to unprotect and delete any delete protected files it encounters.
    This is not practical when running BackUp from a script.
    This switch automatically makes BackUp unprotect and delete all
    delete protected files it encounters.

    FORCEDELETE is mutually exclusive with SKIPDELETE.

  SKIPDELETE/S
    During the cleaning process BackUp normally asks you if you
    like to skip or delete any delete protected files it encounters.
    This is not practical when running BackUp from a script.
    This switch automatically makes BackUp skip all delete
    protected files it encounters.

    SKIPDELETE is mutually exclusive with FORCEDELETE.

  VERBOSELOG/S
    Specify this to produce a verbose log. This will be ignored
    if no logging method was specified.
    Verbose log will add logging of all directories that BackUp
    enters. The complete path of all files and directories will
    not be displayed in verbose mode, instead a sort of graphical
    tree will be displayed.

  DONTCLRSTAT/S
    This prevents the stats window from being cleared between
    messages. This is useful if you run both CLEAN and BACKUP
    automatically and then save the stats.
    If omitted the stats window will be cleared as usual, ignoring
    saved prefs.

  LOGSTAT/S
    Enable logging to the stats window. This also causes the
    stats window to not be cleared before the finished message
    is displayed.
    If omitted, no logging to the stats window will be done
    even if this is saved in the prefs.

  LOGCON/S
    Enable logging to the console that BackUp was started from.
    If omitted, no logging to the console will be done even if
    this is saved in the prefs.

  LOGFILE/K
    This is used both as a switch to enable logging to a file
    and to specify that file. If omitted, there will be no logging
    to a log file even if that is saved in the prefs.

  SKIPFILE/K
    Use this to specify a skiplist file to load.
    If omitted the skiplist file saved in the GUI will be used.
    If you have specified a default skiplist in the prefs but
    don't want to use any skipfile you can simply specify a
    skiplist file that does not exists, f.ex: SKIPLIST=0.

  ERRFILE/K
    This is used both as a switch to enable automatic saving of
    the error list to a file and to specify that file.

  STATFILE/K
    This is used both as a switch to enable automatic saving of
    the stats window to a file and to specify that file.


  See @{"Usage/The main menu/Log" link usage 452} for more details about the logging
  and test mode parameters.


@endnode

@node news "News.."

  @{fg shine}@{b}News and Changes
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

  @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added a verify byte-by-byte funciton in the Misc menu.
          Useful to test if a backup is truly perfect, or if
          it has bit errors.

  @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Better and more accurate speed calculation that tries
          to only calculate the actual copy time.

  @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added "Copy only newer" files as an option.

  @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Fixed some link recognition. It always found unresolvable
          links as different and recreated them, even if they were equal.

  @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Fixed not logging files in test mode.

  @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Human readable timestamps in the log and fixed printing
          of protection bits.

  @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Don't print data speed in cleaning mode. It is pointless.

  @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Don't clear the stats window when running more than one
          process in a row, like backup after cleaning.

  @{b}v1.80@{ub} (140606)
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Fixed crash when copying 2GB+ files.
  
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Added a menu item: "Target is FAT file system". Use this when
     backing up to a partition with FAT file system to prevent
     BackUp from copying existing files over and over. The reason
     is that FAT can only store even seconds (0,2,4,6,..) in the
     file timestamp so it will not match the Amiga file timestamp.
   
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Also added auto-detection of FAT file system when doing an
     incremental backup.
   
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Added a synchronize mode. When clicking Clean first you will be
     asked if it should automatically backup when finished. Saves
     you some time when synchronizing backups.
   
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} BackUp will automatically skip the ".recycled" dir when present
     in the root of a SFS/2 or JXFS partition. No need to manually
     put it in the skiplist anymore.
   
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Fixed size calculation for big files (2-4GB). Files over 4GB
     will be correctly copied and calculated, except in test mode.
     The "N bytes extra space was needed" may be wrong with 4GB+ files.
  
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Made it possible to select files over 2GB for the skiplist.
  
  @{fg fill}**@{fg text} Fixed some menu text entries.

  @{b}v1.71@{ub} (110919)
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an average copying speed in kB or MB/s that will show after
    it is finished. Mostly interesting when you make the first complete
    backup since all time is considered, not just during actual copying.

  @{b}v1.70@{ub} (091103)
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added file size limitation so that you can select that files over
    a given size should not be copied. The new option is in the Backup
    menu.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added two options to prevent the setting of Amiga protection bits
    and Amiga file comments. Useful if you are backing up to a file
    system that cannot save these attributes, such as an USB memory
    or over Samba network.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Restructured the menu a bit to be overviewable.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Enabled multi-select to the skip file requester used when adding
    large files to be skipped.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed an exit failure if the CLI arguments were incorrect. Now
    BackUp should exit cleanly even if there was an error during
    startup, such as if incorrect CLI arguments were given.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug with the file size filter in the ASL requester
    being left enabled sometimes when picking a log file name
    for example.

  @{b}v1.63@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Replaced the ever buggy AFC tasker class, which was used for the backup
    sub process, for custom code. People noticing an exit problem on OS4.1
    beta versions should be fine now.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When creating a local relative softlink an additional slash was added
    to the path.

  @{b}v1.62@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fix for reading softlinks on MorphOS which has a slightly different
    implementation of dos/ReadLink(). This problem could show itself
    when cleaning as BackUp thought everything was softlinks and cleaned
    away your entired backup everytime a clean was performed.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Cleaning softlinks didn't work as they were incorrectly interpreted
    as directories.

  @{b}v1.61@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} BackUp always set the archive bit on directories it had searched
    even if they already had the archive bit set when copying by the
    archive bit.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If BackUp was interrupted using Ctrl-C when in shellmode and
    logging to a logfile was used, the file was not closed.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If you did not have any config saved from the GUI, BackUp would not
    read the skipfile if you used BackUp from CLI with the SKIPFILE
    parameter.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Changed the file date qualification to compare for whole seconds
    only, not ticks. This may help when backing up to USB sticks which
    don't use an Amiga file system.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Changed the output in verbose/non verbose log mode. Now all files
    that were copied or deleted will always be displayed. No distinction
    between small and large files. In normal mode they will be displayed
    with complete path.
    In verbose mode, all directories BackUp enters will be logged and
    the files will not have a path but instead be displayed using an
    ASCII graphical tree. In verbose mode all changes to protection bits,
    file comments and file dates will also be logged.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Changes in protection bits no longer qualifies for a backup of a file.
    Instead only the bits will be updated unless size or date also differs.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} BackUp didn't update file comments, date or protection bits on
    directories that was only searched, not created.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} A side effect of running BackUp from shell was that the task
    priority of the shell was raised by 1 for every run. This made
    BackUp behave strangely after a few runs when the priority got
    high enough.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Better logging of various errors.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a small bug in the "Set path from Source/Target ..."
    code and made it more logical.

  @{b}v1.60@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now BackUp recreates real softlinks on the target instead of always
    copying the files and directories the files points to. Copy the link
    targets as real files and dirs is still available as an option though
    to make it possible to create link-less backups.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an option to create emtpy directories for those directories
    that were put in the skiplist.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} BackUp is now able to replace an old file or softlink with a new
    directory when backing up a second time. In the same sense a
    file can be replaced by a softlink, and a softlink can be replaced
    by a file or directory.
    Even an (empty) directory can be replaced with a file or softlink
    without producing an error message.
    Replacing a non-empty directory with a file is not possible without
    performing a Clean operation first though.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Clean is able to delete anything that is not exactly the same as
    on the source. For example if a backup contains a file, but
    the source now contains a link with the same name instead,
    the file will be deleted during a clean.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Does not set the archive bit on directories that were copied unless
    "Backup by the archive bit" is selected.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} When picking large files and directories for the skiplist the file
    requester will keep opening automatically for selection of more
    files and directories to add to the skiplist until you are done
    and click Cancel in the file requester.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Tried to reduce the graphics updates a bit by removing the
    printing of directory names when exiting directories.

  @{b}v1.50@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now BackUp can follow and backup links, or ignore links completely.
    Note: Links will be copied as real files and directories!

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the argument SHELLMODE/S which will prevent the window
    from opening until the clean/backup has finished. If AUTOQUIT/S
    is used together with SHELLMODE the window will never open.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added FORCEDELETE/S and SKIPDELETE/S to prevent the requester
    from appearing during the clean process if any delete protected
    files is encountered.

  @{b}v1.45@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Corrected the bug which sometimes caused a Grim Reaper on
    startup when used on OS4.

  @{b}v1.44@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} BackUp no longer creates empty directories for directories that
    are in the skiplist.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made CLI argument error handling more rubust with a few bugs
    fixed and more error messages. (If you accidently misspelled
    an argument before, strange things could happen.)
    Now BackUp quits if there was an error during argument parsing
    instead of continuing with the argumens it actually could parse.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Suppressed the requester about converting paths in skipfiles
    when run with arguments from CLI to make CLI scripts run
    without user interaction.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The requester about not all paths could be converted in the
    skiplist now has an Abort option.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a crash when continuing from pause that I introduced in
    v1.43 when I actually though I fix a possible crash!
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made the logging menu a bit more intuitive: Now Verbose log
    cannot be selected unless you also select somewhere to put this
    verbose log.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The priority of the GUI is now set to 1 more than the sub process
    to make it optimally responsive. I noticed that when starting
    BackUp with a priority lower than 0, it didn't respond to pause
    or stop until after a while due to the subprocess still having
    priority 0.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added an option to copy files that do not exist in the target
    even though the archive bit is set in the source when backing
    up using the archive bit. Without this, files that accidently
    have the archive bit set won't ever be backed up.

  @{b}v1.43@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the option to backup depending on the archive bit
    instead of comparing size, date and protection bits in
    general.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If something was hogging the CPU and you clicked on some
    button more than once before anything happened BackUp might
    have crashed due to the subprocess getting out of synch
    with the main program. This should be more rubust now.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed a bug that calculated the created new files size.
    incorrectly.

  @{b}v1.42@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it is possible to browse a directory BackUp has just
    created and is working in. This was not possible before.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the closegadget in the window works to quit BackUp.
    The bug in MorphOS that had me disable it a long time
    ago has been fixed now. Please report any problems!!

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made it possible to pause or stop while copying a large
    file. I noticed that when backing up video files it could
    be quite useful to be able to stop or pause immediately.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now only logging the entering of a directory in verbose mode.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now logging creation of directories in non-verbose mode.

  @{b}v1.41@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} If a path to something was empty a random string
    could have appeard in for example an ASL-requester.

  @{b}v1.4@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} I have changed the communication between the main
    process and the backup process to use message ports
    instead of just a signal and shared memory.
    Most other parts still use shared memory though
    as both processes is part of the same executable.
    Please report any malfunctioning with emulated
    systems (MOS/OS4/Amithlon/..)!
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The time doesn't use battclock resource anymore
    but dos.library so people without a battery
    clock will be able to see how long it took
    now too.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now BackUp can be used in a script to automatically
    backup many different directories or partitions as
    I have added a couple of CLI-arguments which can
    make BackUp start and operation immediately and
    then quit automatically allowing a script to
    execute BackUp for many different locations at
    once without user-intervention!
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a safety requester before cleaning as I
    accidently cleaned my GeekGadgets GCC-installation
    when betatesting! :-(   (Not used when compiling
    BackUp though :))
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can see how many bytes were deleted
    after a Clean operation.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a Test Mode so that you can simulate
    a backup or cleaning to see how many bytes that
    would be copied and how much space that would be
    required before you start for real.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added some more info to the stats in the main
    window including how much space was actually
    required, not just how much was copied which
    usually is alot more.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Made it possible to not clear the list between
    every operation but keep old info.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added the possibility to log all directories
    and files that BackUp traverses or skips. This
    can be logged to the stats window, the console
    or a file in verbose or normal mode.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now BackUp remembers the paths for different
    things, not just use the latest path picked
    in an ASL-requester.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The protection bits, date and comment was not
    set correctly for directories other than those
    in the root during a backup operation.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Doesn't ask to unprotect an undeletable file
    while cleaning anymore unless the file actually
    is delete protected.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Changing the skiplist during a paused operation
    didn't work quite as expected before.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Changing the source and target while backing up
    does not cause the backup or clean to change its
    root directory too as it did in pre v1.4.
  
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Pressing Stop while paused will not require you
    to press continue (Backup/Clean) anymore to make
    the stop take effect.

  @{b}v1.31@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a byte counter so that you can see how many
    bytes were copied or updated, not just how many files.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a Help entry in the menu which will bring
    up the text shown at startup of the program.

  @{b}v1.3@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can see how many files has been scanned,
    copied and failed during an operation.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now all errors are listed in a window so that you
    can see exactly what files that failed, if any.

  @{b}v1.2@{ub}
  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} There is a clean function which makes you able to
    remove all old files from your backup unit without the need
    to manually spend hours tracking down files that are old!
    By "old" I mean not existing on the primary unit any more.

  @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The time for an operation, like the backing up,
    is displayed when the operation is finished.


@endnode

